      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-code-verification-criteria",
      "rationale": "Patch-test verification against analytical linear-elastic solutions confirmed correct element formulation implementation (max displacement error 0.03%). Abaqus benchmark suite results for contact problems are publicly documented. Method of manufactured solutions applied to the contact stress sub-problem; residual norms converged to machine precision. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2 for MRL 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-discretization-criteria",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the tibial tray model (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~340k, fine: ~1.36M). Richardson extrapolation yielded a Grid Convergence Index (GCI) of 1.8% for peak contact stress at the fine mesh level, below the 5% acceptance threshold. The production mesh uses the fine discretization. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-test-conditions-criteria",
      "rationale": "Cadaveric validation experiments were conducted in a temperature-controlled laboratory (22 ± 1 °C) using a servo-hydraulic materials testing system. Specimen preparation, fixture alignment, and load application protocols are fully documented in the validation test plan (VTP-ORTHO-2024-01). Loading waveforms were recorded and compared to ISO 14243-1 gait profiles; deviations were characterised and incorporated into boundary condition uncertainty estimates. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-output-comparison-criteria",
      "rationale": "Predicted peak contact stress and full stress-distribution maps were compared against DIC and pressure-film experimental measurements across six cadaveric specimens and two loading scenarios. Quantitative comparison used mean absolute error (MAE), RMS error, and the ASME V&V 20 validation metric U_val. All metrics fell within pre-specified acceptance bands (MAE ≤ 5%, RMS ≤ 8%, U_val ≤ 0.15 MPa). Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-qoi-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — peak tibial tray contact stress — is directly linked to the clinical failure mode of concern (aseptic loosening driven by fatigue at the tray–bone interface). A formal QoI traceability matrix maps each computational output to its corresponding clinical endpoint and regulatory acceptance criterion. Secondary QoIs (stress distribution uniformity, subsurface shear stress) are also tracked. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-val-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used cadaveric tibial specimens implanted with the same tibial tray geometry as the device under assessment. Loading conditions replicate ISO 14243-1 gait profiles representative of the COU population. Specimen bone density distribution characterised by DXA scanning; results span the clinical range (T-score −2.5 to +0.5). Geometric and material similarity to the COU is documented in the validation relevance assessment report (VRA-ORTHO-2024-01). Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-solver-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was confirmed for all load steps: force residual norm below 1×10⁻⁴ and displacement correction norm below 1×10⁻⁵ at each increment. Contact penetration tolerance set to 0.001 mm; no spurious contact oscillations detected. Time-step sensitivity study confirmed results are insensitive to increment size within ±0.5%. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-use-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation execution checklist was followed for all production runs, covering mesh import, material assignment, boundary condition application, and output request configuration. An independent analyst performed a blind re-run from archived inputs; results agreed to within 0.1% for all QoIs, confirming absence of user-introduced variability. Checklist and re-run records are archived. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-model-form-criteria",
      "rationale": "Cortical and cancellous bone are modelled as transversely isotropic linear-elastic continua; the UHMWPE tibial insert uses a validated elastic–plastic constitutive model calibrated against ISO 5834-2 coupon data. Model form was selected following a structured review of literature on bone constitutive behaviour at physiological strain rates. Viscoelastic creep of bone was scoped out as non-influential at the loading rates of interest, supported by sensitivity analysis showing <1% change in peak stress when creep is included. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-model-inputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "All material properties are sourced from peer-reviewed literature or in-house coupon testing with documented traceability. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (5000 samples) was performed on cortical bone Young's modulus (CV 15%), cancellous bone modulus (CV 25%), and UHMWPE yield stress (CV 8%), propagating input uncertainty through to peak contact stress. The 95th-percentile predicted stress remains 12% below the fatigue endurance limit. Input uncertainty report (IUR-ORTHO-2024-01) is archived. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-test-samples-criteria",
      "rationale": "Six cadaveric tibial specimens were used in validation testing; specimen demographics (age 58–74, BMI 22–31, bone density T-score −2.5 to +0.5) are documented and span the intended clinical population. Sample size justification is provided in the validation plan based on expected inter-specimen variability from pilot data. Specimen preparation and storage protocols followed ASTM F2083. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ortho-input-equivalency-criteria",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed comparing model input values used in validation simulations against those used in the COU simulations. Bone geometry was derived from CT scans of the actual validation specimens; implant geometry was identical (same CAD file). Loading boundary conditions in validation simulations were set from recorded actuator force–displacement data, not nominal ISO profiles, ensuring direct correspondence. Residual mismatches (e.g., specimen-specific vs. population-mean bone density) are quantified and incorporated in the UQ analysis. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    }
